Rewards API – Spring Boot Project

A Spring Boot REST API that calculates customer reward points based on transactions from the last three months.

Features
Calculate reward points per customer
Monthly reward aggregation
Total reward points calculation
Fetch rewards for all customers
RESTful API design
Global exception handling
H2 in-memory database
Unit and integration testing for Service, Controller, and Repository layers
Technologies Used
Java 17 (or Java 11)
Spring Boot
Spring Web
Spring Data JPA
H2 In-Memory Database
Maven
JUnit 5
Mockito
MockMvc
Eclipse / Spring Tool Suite (STS)
Project Overview

This project is a Spring Boot RESTful Web API developed to calculate customer reward points based on purchase transactions over a three-month period.

A retailer offers reward points to customers based on the following rules:

2 points for every dollar spent over $100 in each transaction
1 point for every dollar spent between $50 and $100 in each transaction
No points for purchases of $50 or less
Example

For a transaction of $120:

Amount between $50 and $100 → 50 points
Amount above $100 → 20 × 2 = 40 points
Total Reward Points = 90

The API calculates:

Reward points earned by each customer per month
Total reward points earned by each customer across all months
API Endpoint
Get Rewards by Customer ID

GET /api/rewards/{customerId}

Example Request
http://localhost:8080/api/rewards/101
Example Response
{
  "customerId": 101,
  "customerName": "John",
  "monthlyRewards": {
    "January": 90,
    "February": 25,
    "March": 150
  },
  "totalRewards": 265
}
Implementation Details

The reward calculation logic is implemented in:

RewardCalculator.java

Rules Applied
if (amount > 100) {
    points += (amount - 100) * 2;
    points += 50;
} else if (amount > 50) {
    points += amount - 50;
}
Dynamic Month Calculation

Months are not hardcoded.

Month names are dynamically generated using:

transactionDate.getMonth()
               .getDisplayName(TextStyle.FULL, Locale.ENGLISH);

This satisfies the requirement:

Do not hardcode the months

Database Configuration

The project uses:

H2 In-Memory Database

This helps with:

Easy local testing
No external database setup required
Faster execution
Simplified demonstration for interview assignments
H2 Console
http://localhost:8080/h2-console
Login Details
Property	Value
JDBC URL	jdbc:h2:mem:rewardsdb
Username	sa
Password	(blank)
